      <hedline>
        <hl1>Energy From Waste</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Delaware Agriculture Secretary Jack Tarburton on Aug 11 editorial on protecting Chesapeake Bay from agricultural runoff (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re an Aug. 11 editorial on the improving but fragile state of the Chesapeake Bay:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re an Aug. 11 editorial on the improving but fragile state of the Chesapeake Bay:</p>
        <p>As you note, to have a sustainable poultry industry and meet Federal water-quality goals, regulation alone is not enough. We must have land-use rules that allow farmers to continue to grow chickens for the grocery shelf and dispose of waste in an environmentally sensitive way.</p>
        <p>Few people want to face the economic impact of putting many of these farms out of business. However, there is technology that can convert poultry waste into electricity, generating renewable energy. To make this technology economically viable in Delaware and other states, Congress recently enacted a limited tax credit for those governments that use it. This is the kind of initiative needed to meet environmental challenges at the local level.</p>
        <p>JACK TARBURTON  Secretary of Agriculture  Wilmington, Del., Aug. 18, 1999</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
